<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38164c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38164c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38164c"> 164(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ab = heart / ka = double</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The oldest religious texts suggest that the Egyptians always associated the Last Judgment with the weighing of the heart in a pair of scales, and in the illustrated papyri of the Book of the Dead great prominence is always given to the vignette2s in which this weighing is being carried out. <mark>The heart, <i>ab</i></mark> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was taken as the symbol of all the emotions, desires, and passions, both good and evil, and out of it proceeded the issues of life. It was intimately connected with the <mark><i>ka</i> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> i.e., the double</mark> or personality of a man, and several short spells in the Book PER-T EM HRU were composed to ensure its preservation (Chapters XXVI-XXXB). <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a> (1920) 22</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
